Joyce knows better than most:
Utopia is neither serene, clean nor a dream:
It is as painful perhaps  to be awakened from a vision as to be born.

There are sins or (let us call them as the world calls them) evil memories which are hidden away by humanity in the darkest places of the heart but they abide there and wait. Many may suffer their memory to grow dim, let them be as though they had not been and all but persuade themselves that they were not or at least were otherwise.
Yet a chance word will call them forth suddenly and they will rise up to confront them in the most various circumstances, a vision or a dream, or while timbres and harp soothe their senses or amid the cool silver tranquility of the evening or at the feast, at midnight, when they are now filled with wine. Not to insult over them will the vision come over one that lies under her wrath, not for vengeance to cut them off from the living but shrouded in the piteous vesture of the past, silent, remote, reproachful.

